task.summary: Default task

Started working on Simd like problem.
I like the way I was able to formulate this. The formulation of IsNumber loops over all the squares on the board and just introduces a constraint that that square's number is a valid solution. I suspect this will make solving very, very fast (about as fast as possible). Hopefully all the constraints can work that way (I think they can).
Speed is important because my next step will be generation of all possible satisfied constraints and puzzle generation should be much faster.
Lots of progress on Simd stuff

Generating constraints
This approach seems like it is really efficient. By presupposing the solution, we can reduce the number of constraints significantly.

Big refactoring
Cleaned things up. Now I don't have one giant file but rather several smaller better organized files.
More Constraints

Functional puzzle generator
I seem to have created a puzzle generator that works. I went with an approach that sketches out not just the board and the solution but also a "plan". This plan allows me to define the order of deductions. This helps guide the creation of constraints so that you don't end up with stupid problems where there are constraints that define secondary variables but those variables don't affect any other variables.
The plan is a hierarchical description of the solution order. I think it is rich enough to create sufficiently interesting or complex problem.
What is current missing is the "trim" capability to get rid of redundant constraints. I'm not sure if this should be done locally as we construct constraints or globally at the end. I have to think about which is more efficient but also make sure it doesn't negatively impact the "fun" factor of each puzzle.
Ultimately, what I expect to happen is that through some random process we will synthesize a board, a solution and a plan. Then the puzzle builder will identify a set of clues that are consistent and well specified subject to those constraints.
For harder puzzles, I think it will be necessary/interesting for secondary variables to have multiple solutions. In other words, the criteria for "trimming" the system should be that the primary variable always has a unique solution but that the secondary variables are not required to have a unique solution. The number of solutions for secondary variables could be used as a measure of "hardness".
Finally, although we currently synthesize the constraints to be consistent with a specifical a priori solution. When we trim, we don't need to maintain that unique solution, only the unique solution on the primary variable.
Got the trim function working.

Actually working
I fixed a bug in trim and added a random board generator. Plugging those together got the generator synthesizing puzzles. Even more interesting, the current puzzle it spits out (which is deterministic because of the random seed) is actually quite interesting. I'm going to remove IsNumber though, it is too direct.

Added checks for bogus problems
This code checks to make sure there actually are solutions to the base problem
Cleaned up some warnings (and turned others off)
Tried to simplify PrimaryConstraints
This actually looks like an interesting problem

Had to add primary expressions or I couldn't get a solution
I'm not sure adding the primary expressions was a good idea because the end result was that you didn't need the secondary variables at all. Better to simply throw an exception that a well-posed problem statement can't be found than to spit out a lame problem.
Got rid of primary constraints

Generated a puzzle using paths
I've got a random path generator in here now and I generated a puzzle that seems to be OK. I need to try it out more.

Produced an interesting puzzle
I'm not happy about the CPU time required to synthesize one puzzle, but at least the generator is working.
Now, I really need to work on visualization! It is getting tedious to transcribe these and try and solve them in textual format.
Generate in JSON notation?

Created a new problem generator
I call this the Scuptor approach. It generates all valid constraints. At that point, it confirms that a solution exists for the specified solution. Once that is established, it randomizes and sorts (by priority) those constraints and attempts to eliminate them one by one. If eliminating a constraint would break the "plan" (represented by the DTree class) for dependencies between variables, then the constraint cannot be eliminated. If the constraint doesn't break the plan, then we check to make sure a unique solution exists if the constraint is eliminated. If so, the constraint is removed...otherwise we keep it.
This seems to work (even for purely secondary constraints!). But the number of constraints ends up being pretty high. I'm curious whether this could be a measure of difficulty?

We seem to have a pretty robust little algorith here
For 3-4 variables, it seems to consistently produce solutions that are about 6-8 constraints. It does seem to find lots of random starting points that don't have a solution, but it prunes them quickly.

Fixed a bug in sorting
Now I use all possible valid constraints and it seems to very consistently get rid of primaries if at all possible.

Need to start testing
Things are getting too complicated and too much of what I'm running as an application is really a test. So I'm getting serious about testing. I installed ScalaTest through Maven and I created a tests directory (I figured out that I have to "Mark" the directory as a tests directory).
Now I'm figuring out how to trigger the test runners in IDEA. Then, I can start writing the tests I need to validate all this stuff. In the short term, the critical piece is debugging the new path generation stuff.

I think it might be some kind of bug in IntelliJ, the presentation compiler, the fast compiler or whatever zinc-y kind thing they are doing to compile because it looks perfectly valid to me.

Basic puzzle builder working

Other than that, it seems to be working as expected and it is very simple (and I suspect quite efficient due to the solver on the stack approach).

Implemented a better puzzle solver
The previous solver was flawed, but I reimplemented the sculptor algorithm and it was almost trivial. I need to add the random element to puzzle construction, but that should be pretty easy.
